If I make some changes to the `Book` message, I can generate a diff output like this. It only includes things that are removed or changed (insertion counts as change).

```
PackagesDiff {
    packages: BTreeMapDiff {
        altered: {
            "com.book": PackageDiff {
                entities: BTreeMapDiff {
                    altered: {
                        "Book": Message(
                            MessageDiff {
                                fields: BTreeMapDiff {
                                    altered: {
                                        3: FieldDiff {
                                            name: None,
                                            type_: Int32,
                                            label: NoChange,
                                            default: NoChange,
                                        },
                                    },
                                    removed: {
                                        2,
                                    },
                                },
                            },
                        ),
                    },
                    removed: {},
                },
            },
        },
        removed: {},
    },
}
```

## Try it out

You can play with it yourself. There are two CLI tools in the `validation` crate at the moment, which allow you to parse and diff arbitrary protocol buffer files. Note that not all functionality is implemented. Run these from within the `validation` folder.

```bash
# parse protoc file
cargo run --features tools --bin parse -- --format json path/to/file.proto

# parse protoc file (show raw data)
cargo run --features tools --bin parse -- --raw path/to/file.proto

# generate diff between two files
cargo run --features tools --bin diff -- path/to/a.proto path/to/b.proto
```

## Further ideas

- We could use the same parsing strategy and data structures for the frontend, which would allow us to render protocol buffer definitions and make them searchable.

**This is a draft PR, feel free to look at it but understand that it is not quite ready for review.**

# Introduces

The `buffrs gen|generate --lang <lang>` command for the cli interface.

`buffrs::build(Language::Rust)` which installs all missing and outdated dependencies and then compiles all dependencies and outputs the generated code into `proto/build`

`buffrs::include!("<dependency-package-id>")` for easy usage of the generate code

# Example

In a buffrs project the cargo intgeration is now super simple!

Given a buffrs project which depends on the `demo` api package which contains only one proto file:

`proto/vendor/demo/demo.proto`: 
```proto
syntax = "proto3";

package demo;

message Demo {}
```

Building / installing the protocol buffers now only requires:

`build.rs`: 
```rust
fn main() {
    buffrs::build(buffrs::Language::Rust).unwrap();
}
```

If any dependencies are missing during the build process they will be automatically downloaded from the registry!

This means you can check out any buffrs + cargo project and `cargo run` will just work™

(And of course buffrs has to be added to the Cargo.toml as build dependency and direct dependency, and tonic + prost as normal dependencies)

---

The application code now only needs to do a `buffrs::include` to include the generated code

`src/main.rs`: 
```rust
mod protos {
    buffrs::include!("demo");
}

fn main() {
    dbg!(protos::demo::Demo {});
}
```
